         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <persName>
                  <name key="Pius">Pio</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Carinus">Carino</name>
               </persName> bo<supplied reason="lost">nae me</supplied>
               <lb n="2" break="no"/>mori<supplied reason="omitted">a</supplied>e. <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Aquila">Aqu<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ila</supplied>
                  </name>
               </persName>
               <gap reason="lost" quantity="3" unit="character"/>
               <lb n="3"/>posuit.</ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To Pius Carinus of ha[ppy memory]. Aqu[ila ] set (this) up.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription, carved into plaster, is either a copy or a forgery. I was
                    not able to find any other inscription with the name “Pius Carinus,” but
                    “Carinus” and “Pius” come up quite often in conjunction with one another in
                    reference to Marcus Aurelius.</p>
         </div>
